            <c02 level="class">
               <did>
                  <unitid type="work">poems.epww</unitid>
                  <unittitle type="uniform" label="Uniform Title:">
                     <title render="doublequote" linktype="simple">[Epitaph on Sir William Williams]</title>
                  </unittitle>
                  <unittitle label="First Line:">
                     <title linktype="simple">Here, foremost in the dangerous paths of fame,</title>
                  </unittitle>
                  <unitdate normal="1775" era="ce" calendar="gregorian">1775</unitdate>
               </did>
               <bibliography>
                  <bibref title="https://www.thomasgray.org/resources/biblp.shtml#S/H_1966"
                          linktype="simple">Starr/Hendrickson (eds.), <title render="italic" linktype="simple">Complete Poems</title> (1966),  104-105</bibref>
                  <bibref title="https://www.thomasgray.org/resources/biblp.shtml#LoR_1969"
                          linktype="simple">Lonsdale (ed.), <title render="italic" linktype="simple">Poems</title> (1969),  238-240</bibref>
               </bibliography>
               <scopecontent>
                  <p>Written <extref href="https://www.thomasgray.org/resources/table.shtml#1761"
                             show="replace"
                             linktype="simple">
                        <date normal="176105/176108" era="ce" calendar="gregorian">between May and August
						1761</date>
                     </extref> at the request of one of the executors of <extref href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_William_Peere_Williams,_2nd_Baronet,_of_Clapton"
                             show="new"
                             linktype="simple">
                        <persname normal="Williams, William Peere, Sir, d. 1761">Sir William
								Williams</persname>
                     </extref>, a politician and soldier <persname normal="Gray, Thomas, 1716-1771">Gray</persname> briefly met early in 
							<date normal="176010" era="ce" calendar="gregorian">October 1760</date>, who died <date normal="17610427" era="ce" calendar="gregorian">27 April 1761</date> on an expedition against 
							<geogname normal="Belle Ile (Morbihan, Brittany, France),         island [7010035]">Belle Ile</geogname>.							
							First published, as <title render="doublequote" linktype="simple">Epitaph II. On Sir
							William Williams</title>, in <extref href="https://www.thomasgray.org/resources/glnames.shtml#Mason,         William, 1724-1797"
                             show="replace"
                             linktype="simple">
                        <persname normal="Mason, William,          1724-1797">Mason</persname>'s</extref>
                     <title render="italic" linktype="simple">Poems</title> (<date normal="1775" type="publication" era="ce" calendar="gregorian">1775</date>), <extref href="https://www.thomasgray.org/cgi-bin/view.cgi?collection=primary&amp;edition=1775&amp;part=2&amp;page=62"
                             show="replace"
                             linktype="simple">62</extref>.
						</p>
               </scopecontent>
               <c03 level="item">
                  <did>
                     <unitid type="TGA">mss.0229</unitid>
                     <unitid type="work">poems.epww</unitid>
                     <unittitle label="Title:">
                        <title render="doublequote" linktype="simple">Epitaph on Sir Will<emph render="super">m.</emph> Williams</title>
                     </unittitle>
                     <unitdate normal="1780" certainty="circa" era="ce" calendar="gregorian">1780[?]</unitdate>
                     <physdesc>
                        <extent unit="pages">4</extent>
                        <physfacet>transcript in an unidentified neat and legible hand on
									Whatman paper</physfacet>
                        <dimensions>180 mm x 110 mm</dimensions>
                     </physdesc>
                     <physloc label="Identifier:">
								MS Add. 439, <title render="doublequote" linktype="simple">Poems</title> section, 
								113-116
							</physloc>
                     <physloc label="Building:">The Archives</physloc>
                     <repository>YMAR</repository>
                     <note>
                        <p>MS catalogued by <persname normal="Huber, Alexander">Alexander 
									Huber</persname> in The Archives, York Minster Library &amp; Archives, on <date normal="20070327" era="ce" calendar="gregorian">27/03/2007</date>.</p>
                     </note>
                  </did>
                  <scopecontent>
                     <p>Transcript in an unidentified neat and legible hand, entitled <title render="doublequote" linktype="simple">Epitaph on Sir Will<emph render="super">m.</emph> Williams</title>
								(p. 113) (<title render="doublequote" linktype="simple">Epitaph II.</title> [p. 115]). The
								poem, which is annotated "This Epitaph (hitherto unpublished) was
								written at the request of M<emph render="super">r</emph>. Fred. Montagu,
								who intended to have inscribed it on a Monument at Bellisle, at the
								siege of which this accomplished youth was kill'd, 1761; but for some
								difficulty attending the erection of it, the design was not
								executed" on the title	page, is part of a	section called <title render="doublequote" linktype="simple">Poems</title>, which is 
								separately paginated and has its own table of contents (p. 129), in a
								volume entitled <title render="italic" linktype="simple">Gray's Poems</title>. The book
								carries the bookplate of <persname normal="Gray, Thomas, 1716-1771" source="lcnaf">Gray</persname>'s friend and biographer <extref href="https://www.thomasgray.org/resources/glnames.shtml#Mason, William, 1724-1797"
                                show="replace"
                                linktype="simple">
                           <persname normal="Mason, William, 1724-1797">William
											Mason</persname>
                        </extref>.
							</p>
                  </scopecontent>
               </c03>
